    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living with complexity</h2>
      <p>Standard veterinary care is structured around individual conditions — one problem, one treatment, one specialist. When your cat has two, three, or four overlapping diagnoses, the system often isn't built to manage them together. Each specialist optimises for their condition. Nobody is necessarily optimising for the whole cat. That gap is where owners end up doing the most important work.</p>
      <p>Four of our cats have been complex multi-condition cases. Minou had CKD and diabetes together — each complicating the management of the other, and the dietary needs pulling in opposite directions. Artie had FIV, hyperthyroidism, and asthma, and then neurological decline of unknown origin. Sorbet currently has CKD, FIV, hypertension, and hyperthyroidism. Milton has CKD, arthritis, post-surgical orthopedic complications, and obesity that complicates everything else. In all of these cases, no single appointment covered the full picture unless we brought it in ourselves.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>The core challenge:</strong> The right approach for one condition can be the wrong approach for another. Managing CKD and diabetes means navigating conflicting dietary needs. FIV alongside conditions that require immunosuppressive treatment requires careful recalibration. Managing obesity in a CKD cat means slow, monitored calorie restriction rather than a standard diet plan. These tensions don't always resolve cleanly — but naming them is the first step to managing them.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Keep a single document with all current conditions, medications, and dosing — and bring it to every appointment.</strong> This is especially important in emergencies when you're dealing with a vet who doesn't know your cat's history. You are the continuity of care.</li>
        <li><strong>At every appointment, ask: "Given all of my cat's conditions, are there any interactions or contraindications with what you're recommending?"</strong> Specialists may not have the full picture unless you provide it. The question prompts them to look.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask which condition is the priority right now.</strong> When you can't optimise everything simultaneously, knowing what is most urgent helps you make better decisions about where to focus attention and resources.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask your various vets to communicate with each other when making treatment changes.</strong> This doesn't always happen automatically. Requesting it explicitly, and following up, is part of managing a complex case.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about an internal medicine specialist if no one seems to be managing the whole picture.</strong> A veterinary internist is trained for multi-system disease. If your cat has three or more significant chronic conditions and you feel like the interactions aren't being addressed, an internal medicine consultation is a reasonable and legitimate ask — not an overreaction.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

